<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0319</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Institute of Employment Rights</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submissions on the draft Deregulation Bill to the joint Committee of the House of Lords and the House of Commons, on behalf of the Institute of Employment Rights</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">I have been asked to respond on behalf of the Institute to a request made on behalf of the Committee for the Institute’s views on the questions set out below in relation to the proposal to reduce the power of Employment Tribunals to make recommendations to employers who are found to have discriminated unlawfully. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The Equality Act 2010 provides, at present, that (s124):</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 35.7pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(2)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The tribunal may—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">make</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a declaration as to the rights of the complainant and the respondent in relation to the matters to which the proceedings relate;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">order</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the respondent to pay compensation to the complainant;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(c) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">make</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> an </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">appropriate recommendation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 35.7pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(3) An </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">appropriate recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> is a recommendation that within a specified period the respondent takes specified steps for the purpose of obviating or reducing the adverse effect of any matter to which the proceedings relate—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(a) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the complainant;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">on</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> any other person</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> [emphasis added].</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The draft Deregulation Bill proposes, by </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">cl</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> 2, to amend s124 as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 35.7pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(2)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The tribunal may—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">make</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a declaration as to the rights of the complainant and the respondent in relation to the matters to which the proceedings relate;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">order</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> the respondent to pay compensation to the complainant;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 53.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(c) </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">make</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> an appropriate recommendation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 17.85pt 0pt 35.7pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">(3) An appropriate recommendation is a recommendation that within a specified period the respondent takes specified steps for the purpose of obviating or reducing the adverse effect </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">on the complainant</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> of any matter to which the proceedings relate [emphasis added].</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Our attention is drawn to the following questions which are addressed in turn below:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a) There is a view that if these powers were repealed, then it could mean employers would not take action to tackle discriminatory </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">practises</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> which may mean repeat cases being brought to the Tribunal. Is it fair to make the point that an employer which appears before a tribunal for a case where they had been found against before [is] at risk of a more severe sanction?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">It is not correct to state that an employer which appears before a </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ribunal on a claim of, and is found liable in respect of, discrimination is at risk of a more severe </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">sanction even in a case in which the discrimination in question is the same as that in respect of which a previous finding of liability was made. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Remedies in discrimination claims, as in other employment claims, are generally intended to compensate the Claimant rather than punish the Defendant. The Claimant will be able to recover damages in respect of actual losses flowing from the discrimination, together with injury to feelings and, in appropriate cases, aggravated and (exceptionally) exemplary damages. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">It is conceivable that a Claimant might suffer more serious injury to feelings where the employer is a “repeat offender” but this cannot be assumed. Aggravated damages, which are available in England and Wales, are intended to compensate for injury resulting to the claimant by reason of the poor conduct (over and above the fact of discrimination itself) of the Defendant. They are often wrapped up in injury to feelings compensation in discrimination and, like such compensation, are concerned with the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">compensation</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> rather than </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">punishment</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. The theory is that, for example, malice or other bad intention might exacerbate the injury to feelings suffered by the Claimant.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Exemplary damages are, exceptionally, designed to punish the Defendant rather than to compensate the Claimant. They are available in theory in discrimination claims but are </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">exceptional</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, being available only where the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">compensation</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> would be </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">insufficient to punish the wrongdoer </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">and</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> if the conduct is either (a) oppressive, arbitrary or unconstitutional action </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">by the agents of government</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">, or (b) where the Defendant’s conduct has been </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">calculated by him to make a profit which may well exceed the compensation payable to the claimant</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Again it must be stressed that exemplary damages are almost never awarded and certainly could not be regarded as capable of addressing the point raised in the question.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">b) Are</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the number of cases for discrimination against protected characteristics which are likely to be taken forward to an Employment Tribunal limited by pre-trial mediation such as ACAS’s early reconciliation services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Some discrimination cases settle because of pre-trial mediation including that provided by ACAS. Many claims, however, are by their nature unsuited to mediation (where, in particular, there are significant factual disputes between the parties). What is likely to reduce discrimination, in common with other, employment-related claims </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">is the Tribunal fees introduced in July 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Discrimination c</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">laimant </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">are now required, unless they are exempt, </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">to pay </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">£250 to file a claim with a further £950 </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">in advance of</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> a hearing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c) Is it necessary for cases where an employer is brought before a Tribunal for unlawful discrimination </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">[that the Claimant are] …</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> individuals who have been discriminated against. Is it plausible for indirect victims such as those unhappy about working in environments where discrimination is prevalent to also be heard by the </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Tribunal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Employment Tribunals can only determine complaints from such individuals that they have themselves been discriminated against contrary to the Equality Act 2010. Unless the discrimination made the environment so offensive, intimidating etc to amount to harassment of the individuals complaining there can be no such general complaint.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d) The Government has indicated that the recommendations of the Tribunal are actually non-binding. Does that mean that there is no sanction for failing to implement the Tribunal’s recommendation in a timely manner? Is it likely to be the case that an employer may find it easier to take action to </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">tackle</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">discrimination</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> if recommended by the Tribunal (e.g. the prod of external pressure) rather than act through their internal management chain?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Recommendations are “non-binding” only in the sense that a fa</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">ilure to comply will not amount to contempt of court or similar. It is clear, however, that an employer who fails without reasonable justification to comply with a recommendation is liable to have compensation awarded (or the amount of such compensation increased) in its place (</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">s124(</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">7) Equality Act 2010). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Please do not hesitate to contact me direct if anything in this note is unclear,</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">or if you should require any more assistance.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Aileen </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">McColgan</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">20 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:10pt">Barrister, Matrix Chambers and Professor of Human Rights Law, King’s College London</span></p></body></html>